<!channel> Good morning g35 and happy official graduation day! A couple of last day of class housekeeping things: *Thing 1- Exit Survey* You should have a survey in your inbox from SurveyMonkey asking us for your feedback. Please take a few moments to provide your thoughts around your _entire_ Galvanize experience. As always, if you have additional thoughts to share that you don't want in a feedback form, I'm happy to receive them and pass along constructive criticism. *Thing 2- Alumni Slack* Congratulations on completing this journey! I'll be sending individual Slack invites to graduates to join the gAlumni Slack network and your g35DS Alumni channel. Your gStudent slack access (Slackcess?) will be deactivated and this channel will be archived/removed. *Monday April 24*. Want some extra credit and an archive of this channel's logs of your very own? Here's a script to create your own archive: <https://gist.github.com/Chandler/fb7a070f52883849de35>*Thing3*- Lizzy Roberts, our membership manager, will be reaching out to you soon (if not already), to advise you that your 6 month alumni membership period has begun. This isn't a huge change from your day to day. If you have an assigned locker and you want to keep it, however, please make arrangements with the front desk, as we do bill an admin fee for alums. Keep an eye out for this messaging, and please don't hesitate to ping me with any questions. *Thing 4*- have an AMAZING last day of case studies and go do brilliant things out there.

Much of radiology consists of performing tedious tasks that would greatly benefit from automation, such as segmenting anatomical regions, characterizing lesions and writing reports. Additionally, non-radiologist clinicians who make treatment decisions often do not have the ability to synthesize the myriad components of available clinical information to make the best possible treatment decisions for their patients. Arterysâ€™ goal is to use the latest machine learning technology to solve these problems, help clinicians work more efficiently, and make a dramatic impact on patient outcomes.As a member of the Machine Learning team at Arterys, you will be responsible for developing novel deep learning-based approaches to automate many aspects of medicine, including radiology, disease diagnosis and preventative medicine. Youâ€™ll spend time prototyping novel algorithms, translating them into production-level code, and integrating them into our state-of-the-art cloud-based software. Youâ€™ll develop beautiful tools from messy, real-world datasets and youâ€™ll help improve the lives of millions of patients.

From talent: <http://GamingAnalytics.ai|GamingAnalytics.ai> is a startup that seeks to bring machine learning and artificial intelligence to the management of a specific type of business enterprise: land-based casinos. Casinos are a complex suite of different businesses under one roof - gaming, hospitality, foodservice, entertainment, and real estate - and there is a need to optimize and maximize the allocation of resources and the performance of customer service processes for this type of business. The founder, Kiran Brahmandam, is a long time technology executive and engineering manager focused in this specific space - and the startup is currently finishing its MVP in order to commence the development of the production system while working hand in hand with casinos to build predictive models and machine learning pipelines in order to make better real-time decisions.<http://GamingAnalytics.ai|GamingAnalytics.ai> is looking for daring, entrepreneurial, and hands-on developers who are going to build a very exciting product. This opportunity is particularly exciting for two main reasons:1. Your code will go into a production system - because you will be building machine learning and optimization models for this product2. You will be client-facing - analyzing the business model of land-based casinos we will partner with, their business processes, their data collection sources and practices, and then using this information to design optimization algorithms for them3. You will think about how the user experience, interface, and your predictive models tie in to everything - with the goal of helping executives, floor managers, line managers, and customer service representatives make better decisions regarding resources, and service processesThe Role:Architecture and production api's for the core cognitive business intelligence product, and the goal of designing, developing, and deploying custom optimization and predictive algorithms for specific land-based casino clients. You will work closely with the founder, Kiran, and the software architect Krishnan, in ensuring that the algorithms are appropriate for the use case while the code will work with the architecture and design of the system.At this stage in the startup, there is no typical week or day. This role must be flexible, and entrepreneurially minded in order to identify the priorities of the team given investor meeting schedules, client meeting schedules, and the current status of the product's development. There will be a need for this individual to be able to easily change mindsets between working on a specific client's data, to developing generalizable algorithms that will work on the core product.A Sampling of Projects You Will Work On: - developing generalizable algorithms that will create automatic visualizations given natural language inputs and automated sql queries - working on EDA, machine learning, predictive modeling projects for clients at their site - designing and implementing big data ETL processes that match schemas from the client's data to the core product's schema - performing the role / analysis of a business consultant regarding the client's specific resource optimization problem in their casino, and implementing a solution through a data product prototype / production level solutionRequirements: - Proficient in Python, statistical Python, can pick up new languages fairly well - Strong business acumen and problem-solving skills - Experience leading a team in a managerial role - Strong persuasive and communication skills - An Academic Background in a Quantitative Discipline - i.e. Statistics, Operations Research, Mathematics, PhysicsPreferred Qualifications: - 3+ years experience in a management role, preferably in Sales, Operations - Experience in Business Consulting - Experience managing a codebase and an engineering team - Experience working with enterprise software and business analytics
Thanks!

text: <!channel> Three things: *Thing 1* Break a leg today. You're going to be awesome. *Thing 2* Curious about what's on tap for next week? Check out the Hiring Week schedule here: <https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/10yEZJyQ2G9QOsEHfL6pebMXQDTfUDyBJLjWbTR4IQss/>This is a living breathing document, so bookmark and refer to it often! I've heard your feedback around planning around this schedule, so If you have any questions about what's happening, please check in with me- if I don't know the answer, I'll find out for you. *Thing 3* You have a huge Hiring Week kickoff day tomorrow, and tomorrow night, I encourage you to blow off some steam with me at 6:00pm by singing along to words on a screen. Have a beer, scream some lyrics, and get rewarded for your Karaoke efforts- you may even get a SushiCat of your very own! Sign up here: <https://april7karaoke.eventbrite.com> and PM me your requests ahead of time if you have a go-to. Have a brilliant Capstone Day! See you at 2:00p.

<!channel> Reminder that Expat Woman/Women in Tech is hosting a *Recruiter Panel* tonight at Galvanize! This is a great chance to hear first hand from some recruiters about what they are looking for when they hire. 6 pm onwards â€” Use gvpromo17 for complimentary tickets â€” both men & women welcome :slightly_smiling_face:<https://www.eventbrite.com/e/get-hired-recruiter-panel-and-jobseekers-pitch-recruiters-competition-tickets-32509117646>

Tell me about yourself.Tell me about a project.Why are you interested in this position?Tell me about your work experience.Tell me about your education.Why did you decide on a career/degree in _________?Why did you/are you making a career change?Why are you leaving your current job?What did you like most/least about each of your jobs?What kind of supervisor do you like to work for?What are your strengths?What are your weaknesses?Tell me about a time you failed at something.What 3 words would your coworkers use to describe you?What 3 words would your current supervisor use to describe you?If you had to describe your professional self in 3 words or phrases, which ones would you use?Tell me about a time when you had to manage multiple priorities.Tell me about a time when you worked on a team that didnâ€™t work well together. OR Tell me about a time you didnâ€™t get along with a coworker.Tell me about your biggest professional challenge.Tell me about a time when you were in a leadership role.Why should we hire you?Do you have any questions for me?Take notes on the following:Did the candidate actually answer the question?Did the candidate give examples to support their answers?Did the candidate get off-topic?What did you think about the content of the answers?How was body language?How was eye contact?Did the candidate get negative? (About their past, coworkers, former jobs, etc.)Did the candidate talk about their relevant skill sets and how they relate to the job?Was the candidate specific or vague in their answers?

Some of the claims or guesses â€¦', u'title_link': u'http://blog.precipice.org/why-wesabe-lost-to-mint/', u'service_name': u'blog.precipice.org', u'from_url': u'http://blog.precipice.org/why-wesabe-lost-to-mint/', u'fallback': u'Why Wesabe Lost to Mint - Marc Hedlund's Blog', u'id': 1}]

text: Really great article on data science making a big difference in product.  You probably know of <http://Mint.com|Mint.com>, but may not have heard of Wesabe.  Wesabe was a competitor, and was actually winning, and then Mint took the prize.  The cofounder of Wesabe wrote with a rare level of humility about the failing of his company, and why he thought it failed.  One key part I found illuminating: â€œSecond, Mint focused on making the user do almost no work at all, by automatically editing and categorizing their data, reducing the number of fields in their signup form, and giving them immediate gratification as soon as they possibly could; we completely sucked at all of that. Instead, I prioritized trying to build tools that would eventually help people change their financial behavior for the better, which I believed required people to more closely work with and understand their data. My goals may have been (okay, were) noble, but in the end we didnâ€™t help the people I wanted to since the product failed. I was focused on trying to make the usability of editing data as easy and functional as it could be; Mint was focused on making it so you never had to do that at all. Their approach completely kicked our approachâ€™s ass. (To be defensive for just a moment, their data accuracy â€“ how well they automatically edited â€“ was really low, and anyone who looked deeply into their data at Mint, especially in the beginning, was shocked at how inaccurate it was. The point, though, is hardly anyone seems to have looked.)â€  Itâ€™s an old article but still an insightful one.  Just a smattering of data science, even with low accuracy, was better than making users do the work themselves. â€” <http://blog.precipice.org/why-wesabe-lost-to-mint/>
Itâ€™s 6pm in the Boardroom on the 1st floor

text: <!channel> Graduation is coming up soon, and you want to know the what, where, and when! Your graduation ceremony will be taking place on Friday April 14, at 6:30pm. This is a direct result of your feedback around travel needs for those of you leaving the country, so thanks for giving us the opportunity to hear you and respond! Your official graduation date and last day of class will be on *Tuesday, April 18*. This is due to the extra two days of case study being added to the end of the program in order to accommodate the days missed during the evacuation. These days are considered class days, and attendance is expected per our attendance expectations. As with any class, if you need to miss a date or arrive later in usual, please communicate this to your instructor ahead of time and plan to make up the work (and demonstrate that this work has been completed) in order to excuse the absence. Please invite your family and friends to graduation using this link: <https://g35dsgraduation.eventbrite.com>. You've worked incredibly hard these past few months, and we're all excited to celebrate with you.

attachments: [{u'title': u'Twitch And Mixpanel Fireside Chat', u'text': u'Data scientists and machine learning engineers are both creative, technical and interdisciplinary thinkers, and some of the rarest experts across startups and enterprise companies. Their contributions can impact departments across product, marketing, design, operations, and beyond. But in order for innovative businesses to grow and build excellent products, companies must understand the different applications and values behind each discipline. For this Marchâ€™s Super Office Hours event, Twitch and Mixpanel join forces in a Fireside Chat to discuss why data science and machine learning are two of the most important practices to invest in for company growth. Danny Hernandez, Data Scientist at Twitch, and Jenny Finkel, Head of Machine Learning at Mixpanel, examine how companies use these superpowers to leverage data in more sophisticated ways and build products that win. In this conversation, moderated by Amelia Salyers, Editor of Mixpanel's The Signal, Danny and Jenny will break down the complex concepts of data science and machine learning to help us understand exactly why these two fields will build empires in the new era of technology.', u'title_link': u'https://twitchandmixpanelfiresidechat.splashthat.com/', u'service_name': u'twitchandmixpanelfiresidechat.splashthat.com', u'from_url': u'https://twitchandmixpanelfiresidechat.splashthat.com/', u'fallback': u'Twitch And Mixpanel Fireside Chat', u'service_icon': u'http://d24wuq6o951i2g.cloudfront.net/img/events/id/274/2743345/assets/cfc.shutterstock_512609593-2-.jpg', u'id': 1}]

<@U365TCNH3> I don't think you have to put the flag. Rsync should be able to just start up where it left off. It does checks to make sure the file has been transferred with no corruptions.

this is what i seemed to find, but am a bit paranoid, there are so many flags (append, partial, etc.)â€” seems like though by default that rsync will check if the file is corrupted when it resumes and fix/override it if it is? and i want to make sure iâ€™m not screwing up that functionality with my ignore-existing flag like the append option does

does anyone know for sureâ€¦ if i transfer files using rsync, and the transfer is interrupted, is it sufficient to restart the transfer with the `- -ignore-existing` flag? â€”namely, can anyone confirm with certainty that the file that was in process of transferring while interrupting *wonâ€™t* be corrupted?
Yes, there are many ways to do it. On second thought, you may want to zip into different files and transfer them with different shells.
Different people, different takes :slightly_smiling_face:
Different shells are okay.  This too: <http://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/trust>â€¦
Cool! Thanks!

Don't do different shell sessions, just tar and zip them into one file. You will have to exchange network keys if you are going to be transferring a large number of files - you don't want to do that. You likely won't speed up the whole process anyway.
<@U3P1FCSTT> screen is awesome
<http://aperiodic.net/screen/quick_reference>
would this help? or would the bottleneck be the network upload speed?
just in different shell sessions?
<@U1VA45RE2> how do i scp them in parallel? :flushed:
You can also gzip them individually and scp them in parallel.
Okay! Iâ€™ll try that, thanks!!!
Then you can scp the `tar.gz` file
You can tar the entire directory with all the files and then use gzip with the `-9` flag (I think thatâ€™s the highest level of compression) check the man pages for that one
Ummm, tar and gzip it at the highest compression
Wait, 100 gb...
Write a bash script to use the awscli
in the end probably looking to upload ~ 100 gb of data
each individual file ~ 40-60 mb, but lots of them
you will probably be limited to your network's upload speed
How large are the files youâ€™re trying to transfer?

Hey Jon, this can be accomplished by using "screen". It was briefly mentioned the day we worked together last week (but not in a lot of detail) - you can basically open a new process in a screen, close it, and have it run in the background. This is also how you avoid losing your running processes when you detach from your AWS instance. <http://aperiodic.net/screen/quick_reference>

attachments: [{u'thumb_height': 133, u'thumb_url': u'https://i1.wp.com/tctechcrunch2011.files.wordpress.com/2016/11/google-shop121.jpg?fit=200%2C150&ssl=1', u'thumb_width': 200, u'title': u'Google is acquiring data science communityÂ Kaggle', u'service_name': u'TechCrunch', u'author_name': u'Frederic Lardinois, John Mannes, Matthew Lynley', u'title_link': u'https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/07/google-is-acquiring-data-science-community-kaggle/', u'service_url': u'http://techcrunch.com', u'text': u'Sources tell us that Google is acquiring Kaggle, a platform that hosts data science and machine learning competitions. Details about the transaction remain somewhat vague, but given that Google is hosting its Cloud Next conference in San Francisco this week, the official announcement could come as early as tomorrow.Reached by phone, Kaggle co-founder CEO Anthony Goldbloom declined to deny that the acquisition is happening. Google itself declined “to comment on rumors.”Kaggle, which has about half a million data scientists on its platform, was founded by Goldbloom and Ben Hamner in 2010. The service got an early start and even though it has a few competitors like DrivenData, TopCoder and HackerRank, it has managed to stay well ahead of them by focusing on its specific niche. The service is basically the de facto home for running data science — and machine learning — competitions.With Kaggle, Google is buying one of the largest and most active communities for data scientists — and with that, it will get increased mindshare in this community, too (though it already has plenty of that thanks to Tensorflow and other projects).Kaggle has a bit of a history with Google, too, but that’s pretty recent. Earlier this month, Google and Kaggle teamed up to host a $100,000 machine learning competition around classifying YouTube videos. That competition had some deep integrations with the Google Cloud Platform, too.Our understanding is that Google will keep the service running — likely under its current name.While the acquisition is probably more about Kaggle’s community than technology, Kaggle did build some interesting tools for hosting its competition and “kernels,” too. On Kaggle, kernels are basically the source code for analyzing data sets and developers can share this code on the platform (the company previously called them “scripts”).Like similar competition-centric sites, Kaggle also runs a job board, too. It’s unclear what Google will do with that part of the service.According to Crunchbase, Kaggle raised $12.5 million (though PitchBook says its $12.75) since its launch in 2010. Investors in Kaggle include Index Ventures, SV Angel, Max Levchin, Naval Ravikant, Google chief economist Hal Varian, Khosla Ventures and Yuri Milner.', u'from_url': u'https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/07/google-is-acquiring-data-science-community-kaggle/', u'fallback': u'TechCrunch Link: Google is acquiring data science community Kaggle', u'service_icon': u'https://s0.wp.com/wp-content/themes/vip/techcrunch-2013/assets/images/favicon.ico', u'id': 1}]

from there, if you want to get updates (like git pull), you can do `svn update` in the directory you cloned :slightly_smiling_face:

text: Hi!Hereâ€™s a hack to clone a subdirectory/file to your local machine.Say I want this folder:`<https://github.com/zipfian/DSI_Lectures/tree/master/topicmodeling/cary_goltermann>`You can use `svn``svn checkout <https://github.com/zipfian/DSI_Lectures/trunk/topicmodeling/cary_goltermann>` in the directory you wantNotice you need to change `tree/master` to `trunk`

text: Hey, all! It's unclear to me whether the permissions are correct for the g35 google group, so I'll just post here as well a couple thoughts on week 5. These will quickly get buried in an avalanche of other slacks...(Week 5)It is perhaps a bit ironic that we head into "unsupervised learning" this week, after we are a bit undersupervised in three extra days without classes & sprints ...This extra time offers a good opportunity both to catch up and to plan ahead.You might want to review material already covered, including some of the more challenging sprint problems. Reviewing assessment questions might be a good way to shore up mastery of basics. Beyond that, you should have encountered useful areas perhaps worth at least additional months of study and use.Looking forward, there are only four regular class days before the break.Stay tuned for schedule updates, and please continue to prepare daily.However, the bigger picture involves three new areas of work, not yet fully addressed in DSI:1) Your ongoing research, with your capstone project up next. Over time, this will be your ongoing work projects.2) Your ongoing career development: a search for your next job, and/or how to develop in your present one.3) Your ongoing choice of specialization, which you will need to adapt as long as data science continues to evolve so quickly. (This shows no signs of stopping.)Each of these involves your own choices of where to place your energy, as well as what to defer until later, or maybe just not to pursue at all.--> Hopefully, we have made a strong case that you should never goo too long without spending significant energy on each of these areas! The easiest way to do this is to make all three part of your daily habit and to rebalance as needed.For the capstone, now is a good time to begin brainstorming: both what you might be able to conclude, AND what data you could reasonably obtain. It would be great if you develop ideas this week, discuss them with staff, and at least do a proof of concept of obtaining partial data. Some projets have to pivot due to unanticipated difficulty in obtaining data, or when the data don't say what we guessed they might.For the longer term, recent weeks have probably helped you identify both areas about which you are enthusiastic, as well as tasks you would prefer to avoid. Striking success (and usually even moderate success) tends to compromise between what needs to get done/could get done, and our natural preferences. One young tech retiree told me after his >$100M exit in a company he co-founded (and after having experienced his share of ejections from other companies) that "the key to success is doing what others are unwilling to do."In my opinion, part of the "secret sauce" of Galvanize DSI for students is to expose them to a wide set of skills useful for progress, including ones they could avoid while traversing entire academic programs or careers.--On the other hand, this is only a temporary program. Its ongoing value to you will require forming habits of the learning and problem-solving you are doing now. It is easy to scan blogs, or attend meetups. But as passive activities, you will gain much less from that than if you engage in them actively.The average corporate worker seems to spend relatively little time each day maintaining and building skills, or even thinking deeply about what is new in tech and business. Compared to them, if you maintain even a fraction of your current pace, you will move past the crowd over time.To make this progress, it is critical that you seek it out, and also engage with people who are pursuing and *doing* data science - not just marketing it. So today's non-profound wisdom: life is short - carpe diem, but also do the stuff you know you need to do...:slightly_smiling_face:-Chris

Among other things, this builds interactive sliders that let you see the effects of varying smoothing parameters.

text: <!channel> lend lease and the city have determined that there is no longer any imminent danger now that lend lease installed shoring in the affected portion of the building. however, 543 howard/44 tehama still remains under an evacuation order until lend lease can remove equipment and materials from the area. tehama between 1st and 2nd will remain closed.lend lease will begin the operation of equipment and material removal at 6 am tomorrow and do not have an exact estimate for when this work will be completed.  it is possible the campus could be closed all day. more updates to come in the morning.we are allowed back in the building at this time to retrieve essential personal items one at a time with Sam, one of our security personnel, escorting, until midnight tonight, and then again in the morning at 7 am with Glenda (or another Galvanize team member) escorting. please meet security on the howard side of the building.

attachments: [{u'image_bytes': 125177, u'author_link': u'http://en.wikipedia.org/', u'text': u'Her is a 2013 American romantic science-fiction drama film written, directed, and produced by Spike Jonze. It marks Jonze's solo screenwriting debut. The film follows Theodore Twombly (Joaquin Phoenix), a man who develops a relationship with Samantha (Scarlett Johansson), an intelligent computer operating system personified through a female voice. The film also stars Amy Adams, Rooney Mara, and Olivia Wilde.Jonze conceived the idea in the early 2000s after reading an article about a website that allowed for instant messaging with an artificial intelligence program. After making I'm Here (2010), a short film sharing similar themes, Jonze returned to the idea. He wrote the first draft of the script in five months. Principal photography took place in Los Angeles and Shanghai in mid-2012. The role of Samantha was recast in post-production, with Samantha Morton being replaced with Johansson. Additional scenes were filmed in August 2013 following the casting change.Her premiered at the 2013 New York Film Festival on October 12, 2013. Warner Bros. Pictures initially provided a limited release for Her at six theaters on December 18. It was later given a wide release at over 1,700 theaters in the United States and Canada on January 10, 2014. Her received widespread critical acclaim upon its release, and grossed over $47 million worldwide on a production budget of $23 million.The film received numerous awards and nominations, primarily for Jonze's screenplay. At the 86th Academy Awards, Her received five nominations, including Best Picture, and won the award for Best Original Screenplay. Jonze also won awards for his screenplay at the 71st Golden Globe Awards, the 66th Writers Guild of America Awards, the 19th Critics' Choice Awards, and the 40th Saturn Awards.', u'title': u'Her (film)', u'image_width': 250, u'author_name': u'Wikipedia', u'title_link': u'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Her_(film)', u'image_height': 370, u'image_url': u'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/44/Her2013Poster.jpg', u'fallback': u'wikipedia: Her (film)', u'service_icon': u'https://a.slack-edge.com/bfaba/img/unfurl_icons/wikipedia.png', u'id': 1}]

All,Monday morning, we will cover the MongoDB NoSQL database.  I'll be doing a bit of coding "live".  You are more than welcome to "sit and watch" but if you want to follow along on your own computer, you'll need to go ahead and install MongoDB *ahead* of class (you'll be doing it as part of morning assignment anyway...).  I'll be around before class starts Monday to help you if you have some issues installing it but I won't stop during the lecture for MongoDB installation issue...MongoDB Installation1. To install MongoDB, use your operating system's package manager:* Mac OS X: brew install mongodb* Ubuntu Linux: sudo apt-get install mongodb2. Much like Postgres, you will need to launch the server before using Mongo for the first time.* Mac OS X: brew services start mongodb* Ubuntu Linux: sudo /etc/init.d/mongodb start3. Check your installation by opening the MongoDB Client:* Open a new terminal and type mongo to open up a Mongo shell* Type 'show dbs;' to show the databases you have* You can exit by typing 'exit'

<!channel> ```def stage_score_plot(estimator, train_x, train_y, test_x, test_y):    name = estimator.__class__.__name__.replace('Regressor', '')    learn_rate = estimator.learning_rate    train_scores = np.zeros((estimator.n_estimators,), dtype=np.float64)    test_scores = np.zeros((estimator.n_estimators,), dtype=np.float64)    # Get train score from each boost    for i, train_y_pred in enumerate(estimator.staged_predict(train_x)):        train_scores[i] = mean_squared_error(train_y, train_y_pred)    # Get test score from each boost    for i, test_y_pred in enumerate(estimator.staged_predict(test_x)):        test_scores[i] = mean_squared_error(test_y, test_y_pred)    plt.plot(train_scores, alpha=.5, label='%s Train - Rate %s' % (name, learn_rate))    plt.plot(test_scores, alpha=.5, label='%s Test - Rate %s' % (name, learn_rate), ls='--')    plt.title(name, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')    plt.ylabel('MSE', fontsize=14)    plt.xlabel('Iterations', fontsize=14)```

text: On recent posts:- <@U3NUVB29W> 's advice above should be on our assessments!- <@U3PNWUG2J> : learning spark is a high-value use of your time. We'll get you up and running with it on spark day 1, but there's only limited time to master ml on day 2. So additional sourced could definitely help. Databricks tries to get you to buy their add-ons, so I's suggest starting with spark-only learning. Trick for getting plots even from ipython.Today's lecture code works when you're in a notebook environment with inline plotting.If you're in pure ipython, you can get a plot via sns (seaborn) by just calling the 'show' method on plt (matplotlib.)This works even for fancier sns plot types:```In [3]: plt.plot(range(4), [1,5,2,6])Out[3]: [<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x118073c10>]In [4]: plt.show()In [5]: import seaborn as snsIn [6]: sns.set()In [7]: plt.show()In [8]: plt.plot(range(4), [1,5,2,6])Out[8]: [<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x11bdea5d0>]In [9]: plt.show()In [10]: sns.distplot([1,3,4,3,5,4,8,11])Out[10]: <matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x11c372850>In [11]: plt.show()```

text: Just FYI for those who may not already know, you can add a `.gitignore` file to your repository to ignore staging and committing certain files (for example, you may want to do this to avoid uploading large files (data), files with security keys, etc., .DS_Store, etc.)What Iâ€™m doing is putting any data I have in my repo under a folder called `data` and in my .gitignore I have `data/` This should ignore any folder called `data` at any level in your repo.Also, if you have changes upstream in your github that you donâ€™t have locally (and youâ€™ve made other commits, causing conflicts/inconsistency with your commit historyâ€¦ often youâ€™ll want to `rebase` to maintain the order of your commit history.

```Assessment #1Welcome to our first assessment! You will have 120 minutes to complete the assignment at which time you will be asked to submit a pull request.Time: 120 minutesOpen bookIndividualAssignmentThe goal of this assignment is to fill in each function stub to make the associated test pass.There are 21 questions over these topics in this order:general Python (4 questions)probability (1 question)numpy (2 questions)pandas (2 questions)SQL (3 questions)Math (9 questions)Download the assessment files.Follow these submission instructionssrc/assessment.py contains function stubs for you to fill in. The goal is to make the tests pass. There are 12 problems in the file.Running Unit TestsNeeds Python2.7 or greateryou can check your python version by running this: python -VThis section in the assessment can be tested using the unit tests. You can run the tests with this command from the root directory (assessment-day1/):make testIf you do not have py.test, you may see Import errors. Run the following commands in case you see such errors:pip install pytest. refers to passing test, E is an error in the code and F is a failure. So something that looks like this: ....EFFFFFF means 4 tests passed, one has an error and 6-11 fail.It can be helpful to press enter a bunch of times between each time you run the test so that it's easy to find the beginning of your most recent results.The questions for the math portion of the assessment are in math/math_assessment.pdf. Put your answers in math_assessment.txt. There are no automated tests for this portion of the assessment.At the end of 120 minutes, submit a pull request.Feel free to use any online resources like python documentation and tutorials, your notes, readings and exercises.```

Here is an overview of what I'll be reviewing starting at noon.These are just lists of topics - you may want to take your own notes.Quant stuff to know in general:- Calculus (reviewed 2nd session): mainly single-var, but still need some multi-var- Lin alg (below)- Runtime analysis ("big oh" notation)- Prob- Stat- sw: 'tex' way of entering formulas in text: 	^ superscript, _ underscore, \alpha special characters & operations-----------------------------------------What you need to remember from linear algebra[optional stuff is in square brackets]Cast of characters: scalars, vectors, matricesVectors: concrete and abstract- 2d-3d with fixed basis- physics: something that 'transforms' like a vector (velocity, momentum)- functions: great for linear models, feature vectorsArithmetic of vectors:- addition, mult by scalar- distributive -> linear combinations create subspaces (span)- going backwards from a space to a basis B = {\vec(b_1), \vec(b_2), ... \vec(b_n)}- Once B is chosen, there is exactly one way to express a given vector \vec(v) as:\vec(v) = c_1 * \vec(b_1) + c_2 * \vec(b_2) + ... + c_n * \vec(b_n)Three notions of 'size':1) length of vector2) SEE BELOW: determinant of matrix3) dimension of a vector space--> linear (in-)dependence--> need to build new intuition for this!Arithmetic of vectors (II): dot products--> remember trig? (sin, cosine)- 2-d view on possibly infinite-dimensional spaces- length of projection of \vec(a) on \vec(b)- orthogonality- dot product returns a number; cross product \vec(a) x \vec(b) returns a vector, but only works in 3d.Matrix multiplication(example: try to mult two col vectors)(ex: try wrong matrix times vector)- not symmetric!- transposeLinear transformations: what a matrix 'does'- kernel- image- rank: for rows vs. cols <= dimensions of matrixReally nice matrices: diagonal- have easy eigenvalues, eigenvectors- first idea of how to define determinant and rank- duality between cols and rowsNice matrices:- orthogonal- even better: orthonormal (orthogonal AND columns have length 1)Determinant- nice formula for 2d- try out on ((1,1),(1,-1))--> if you multiply matrix by 5, what does that do to determinant?Inverse- nice formula for 2d'Similar': how matrix changes under change of basis B: A -> B*A*B^(-1)- example: what's the matrix that operates as follows?(1,1)^t -> *2(1, -1)^t -> *1Application: solving A*x = y for x given A, y- more realistic: approximating A*x ~ y--> Habit: A is feature matrix: rows are records, cols are featuresMatrix factorizations:(abbreviations: B=basis, D=diagonal, - A = B*D*B^-1 (you wish, but happens to always work with real D if A is symmetric.)[- A = B*J*B^-1 (always works. J=Jordan form: with diagonal blocks like ((2,1,0),(0,2,1),(0,0,2)))]- A = L*U (L=lower triangular, U=upper triangular)- SVD - good intuition for what a matrix does: A = U^*D*V^(-1) for any A - even not squareTall matrix:- 'good old days' of traditional (frequentist) statsWide matrix:- insufficient number of rows to 'prove' model, so consider only a subset of possible models
